{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/mastering-data-selection-with-pandas-e8768104a39", "time": 1683007228.21474, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/mastering-data-selection-with-pandas-e8768104a39/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Mastering Data Selection with Pandas | by Sadrach Pierre, Ph.D. | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Mastering Data Selection with Pandas", "description": "Pandas is a python library that provides several useful tools for statistical analysis, feature engineering, data selection, data filtering and much more. Data selection and data filtering are useful\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://www.kaggle.com/gregorut/videogamesales", "anchor_text": "Video Game Sales Dataset", "paragraph_index": 1}, {"url": "https://github.com/spierre91/medium_code/blob/master/pandas_tutorials/selecting_data.py", "anchor_text": "GitHub", "paragraph_index": 20}], "all_paragraphs": ["Pandas is a python library that provides several useful tools for statistical analysis, feature engineering, data selection, data filtering and much more. Data selection and data filtering are useful for exploratory data analysis, feature engineering, and predictive model building. In this post, we will discuss some useful methods in Pandas for data selection and filtering.", "For our purposes, we will be working with the Video Game Sales Dataset.", "To start, let\u2019s import the Pandas library and read the data into a Pandas data frame:", "Let\u2019s also relax the limit on the number of display columns:", "Next, let\u2019s print the columns in the data:", "Let\u2019s also print some basic information about the data:", "Now, let\u2019s print the first five rows of data using the \u2018head()\u2019 method:", "Ok, now that we have a decent idea of the column names and types in the data we can perform some basic data selection operations. To start, we can use the \u2018.loc[]\u2019 method to select subsets of our data based on column values. Let\u2019s select video games in the \u2018sports\u2019 genre:", "Let\u2019s print the first five rows of our new data frame:", "Let\u2019s take a look at another column. Let\u2019s select the subset of data corresponding video games for the Wii platform:", "Let\u2019s print the first five rows of data:", "We can also select subsets of subsets. For example, let\u2019s select \u2018Racing\u2019 games played on \u2018Wii\u2019:", "We can also perform this operation with a single line of code using a joint condition:", "And we can add as many conditions as we like. Let\u2019s select Wii racing games that sold more than 1 million units globally:", "We can also select data by row using the \u2018.iloc[]\u2019 method. Let\u2019s select the first 1000 rows of the original data:", "We can also select a random sample of data, using the \u2018sample()\u2019 method:", "If we print the first five rows:", "And print the first five rows in another run:", "We see we get different results. If we want to consistently get the same result, we can set the \u2018random_state\u2019 parameter in the sample method:", "This should give us the same result upon each run. I\u2019ll stop here but I encourage you to play around with the code and data yourself.", "To summarize, in this post we discussed how to select and filter data using the Python Pandas library. We discussed how to use the \u2018.loc[]\u2019 method to select subsets of data based on column values. We also showed how to filter data frames by row using the \u2018.iloc[]\u2019 method. Finally, we discussed how to select a random sample of data from a data frame using the \u2018sample()\u2019 method. I hope you found this post interesting/useful. The code in this post is available on GitHub. Thank you for reading!", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Writer for Built In & Towards Data Science. Cornell University Ph. D. in Chemical Physics."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24cano